        //
        // So, for [3, 6], 2 is a valid answer. 3 is a valid answer.
        // The example output 3 is just one of the valid answers.
        // My logic that 2 is always a valid answer (if l != r) seems to hold.
        //
        // Let's double check the "floor(r/x) - floor((l-1)/x) >= floor(r/y) - floor((l-1)/y) for x < y" part.
        // Let N(x) be the count of multiples of x in [l, r].
